# Workbench directory boundary (`components/workbench/`)

Mirrors **AGENTS.md §7 → Design system** (app shell row). **Canonical shell product doctrine:** **[`docs/decisions/0001-afenda-spatial-os-shell.md`](../../docs/decisions/0001-afenda-spatial-os-shell.md)** (Spatial OS — L1 Utility / L2 Workspace / L3 Command–Intent / L4 Dock) and **[`docs/decisions/0005-workbench-canonical-shell.md`](../../docs/decisions/0005-workbench-canonical-shell.md)**. **Material adoption:** **[`.cursor/rules/material-semantics.mdc`](../../.cursor/rules/material-semantics.mdc)** + **`scripts/check-design-contract.mjs`**. If this rule and `AGENTS.md` diverge, follow `AGENTS.md` and fix this rule in the same PR.

> **`components/workbench/`** is the **single canonical shell**. No other post-login layout-wrapper component exists. `components/nexus/` retains only Lynx summon and Nexus Field (product surface) components — it is no longer the shell host.

## Authority

- **`components/workbench/`** owns **all post-login layout chrome**: `workbench-shell.tsx` (the single canonical mount point), `workbench-surface.tsx` (content region), `workbench-sub-layout.tsx` (nested rail surfaces), L1 utility bar (`utility-bar/workbench-utility-bar.tsx` + all `workbench-utility-*.tsx` widgets), command palette runtime (`workbench-command-layer.tsx`, `workbench-command-context.tsx`), L4 dock stub, mobile rail sheet (`workbench-mobile-rail.tsx`), skip-to-main (`workbench-skip-to-main.tsx`), and the WorkbenchRail component family (`rail/`). No tenant business rules, no DB access, no Server Actions.
- **`components/nexus/`** owns **Nexus Field product surface** (`nexus-page.tsx` and all Nexus Field zone components — pressure, priority lanes, truth map, resolutions, orientation band) and **Lynx summon UI** (`nexus-lynx-summon-context.tsx`, `nexus-lynx-summon.client.tsx`). These are not chrome — they are product surfaces that render inside `WorkbenchShell.children`.
- **IAM auth surfaces** (sign-in, interruption flows) use **`components/auth/`** and **`#lib/auth`** — do not fold IAM workflows into Workbench shell components.

## Shell ownership doctrine

The Workbench shell is **operational spatial infrastructure** (ADR-0001 + ADR-0005), not marketing UI or module feature UI. Mental model: **intent → operational surface → execution → truth resolution**, implemented as **L1–L4** — not "portal/home → module tree."

Every post-login `layout.tsx` mounts **`WorkbenchShell`**. Nested surfaces that need a rail inside an already-mounted shell (org admin, HRM) use **`WorkbenchSubLayout`** — not a second `WorkbenchShell`.

Prioritize, in order:

1. Spatial orientation and operational continuity (dock + command intent + workspace surface)
2. Organization context clarity (slug-bound URLs per locale-first contract)
3. Capability discoverability without hierarchical ERP clutter
4. Layout stability (no padding ↔ dock/rail width drift)
5. Keyboard and accessibility consistency

**Before** visual differentiation, motion novelty, or unconstrained "workspace intelligence" UX.

## Component map

| Component | File | Mount point |
|---|---|---|
| `WorkbenchShell` | `workbench-shell.tsx` | Every post-login `layout.tsx` |
| `WorkbenchSubLayout` | `workbench-sub-layout.tsx` | Nested layouts with a rail (admin, HRM) inside an existing shell |
| `WorkbenchSurface` | `workbench-surface.tsx` | Page-level content region (sticky header + scroll body) |
| `WorkbenchUtilityBar` | `utility-bar/workbench-utility-bar.tsx` | L1 top bar; accepts `mode: "org" | "no-org"` |
| `WorkbenchRail` | `rail/workbench-rail.tsx` | L2 left nav rail (collapsible, slot-driven) |
| `WorkbenchCommandLayer` | `workbench-command-layer.tsx` | L3 command palette (route-configured via sections prop) |
| `WorkbenchDock` | `workbench-dock.tsx` | L4 dock (stub; org surfaces only) |
| `WorkbenchMobileRailSheet` | `workbench-mobile-rail.tsx` | Mobile nav Sheet; driven by `WorkbenchMobileRailProvider` |

## Rules

- **Single shell.** `WorkbenchShell` mounts once per route tree. Do **not** nest a second `WorkbenchShell` inside a child layout — use `WorkbenchSubLayout` for inner rails.
- **Registry-aligned navigation.** Rail slots are always built from capability registries (`ORG_ADMIN_CAPABILITIES`, `HRM_CAPABILITIES`, `PLATFORM_ADMIN_CAPABILITIES`) or typed data contracts (`buildAccountRailSlotsV2`). No orphaned hard-coded `NAV_ITEMS` arrays that drift from path helpers.
- **L1 utility bar widgets.** All utility-bar icon buttons must use `WorkbenchUtilityRoundTooltipButton` / `WorkbenchUtilityRoundTooltipLink` or `WorkbenchUtilityTriggerTooltip` for tooltip consistency. Do not import `#components/ui/tooltip` directly inside `components/workbench/**`.
- **Boring shell.** No animated chrome for novelty; density and calm ERP posture beat dashboard marketing energy.
- **Module-level layouts.** Two-pane and multi-pane shells (e.g. Orbit queue+detail layouts) are feature-level geometry — they live **inside** `WorkbenchSurface.children` and remain feature-owned under `lib/features/<module>/components/`. They must not be confused with `WorkbenchShell` or `WorkbenchSubLayout`.

## Forbidden

- Tenant-scoped **ERP/domain logic** inside `components/workbench/**`.
- **Deep imports** into `lib/features/<module>/data/...` from Workbench shell — consume `#features/<module>` or `#features/<module>/client` barrels only where the shell needs a typed contract.
- **Cross-tenant or slug-from-client** assumptions — org slug and navigation targets come from server guards + path builders; shell components remain presenters of props from RSC parents.
- Adding `nexus-shell.tsx` or `nexus-surface-chrome.tsx` back — those files have been deleted; `WorkbenchShell` is the replacement.
- Creating a parallel `components/dashboard/` shell directory — there is no second shell stack.

## Governance kernel — shell schemas are authoritative

The Workbench shell is **schema-governed**. Every shell surface that accepts
structured slot data — today `WorkbenchRail` (and tomorrow inbox / views /
pinned / recents per **[`docs/_draft/working-memory-rail-plan.md`](../../docs/_draft/working-memory-rail-plan.md)**) — must follow the
**kernel-first** doctrine:

> _The shell Zod schema is the kernel. Per-workbench builders are pure
> mappers. The kernel is the only place new slot fields are added, deleted,
> or constrained._

Rules:

- **Single source of truth.** Each shell surface declares its contract in **one** Zod schema file (today: `components/workbench/rail/workbench-rail.schema.ts`). TypeScript surfaces in the matching `*.types.ts` are **derived** via `z.infer<>` — never hand-edited to add fields the schema does not declare.
- **Builders are pure mappers.** Per-workbench rail-slot builders (`buildAccountRailSlotsV2`, `buildHrmRailSlots`, `buildOrgAdminRailSlots`, `buildPlatformAdminRailSlots`) map domain inputs to the kernel-declared shape and nothing else. They must not synthesize fields that the kernel does not expose; the type checker rejects the surface, and runtime parsers (`parseWorkbenchRailSlotsData`, `parseWorkbenchRailLabels`, `parseWorkbenchRailNavItem`) reject foreign payloads. **Lints to flag:** decorative pills, ambient context strips, rail-level "description" filler, hardcoded "Online · secure session" footers, or any rail content that does not answer a clear operator question (see _Anti-pattern guardrails_ below).
- **Cross-cutting structural changes use codemods.** When a kernel field is added, removed, or renamed, propagate it across builders + layouts with a **`ts-morph` codemod** under `scripts/refactors/<date>-<slug>.ts` rather than editing each call site by hand. Codemods must support both `--dry-run` (default) and `--apply`, must be idempotent, and must be re-runnable in CI on a clean tree (verified by the rail DOM test suite + `pnpm lint` / `pnpm typecheck`). Reference: [`scripts/refactors/2026-05-12-rail-schema-prune.ts`](../../scripts/refactors/2026-05-12-rail-schema-prune.ts).
- **Doctrine validation.** The kernel-first + codemod-driven approach is grounded in the App Router runtime contract: typed slot composition is canonical (see [`.cursor/rules/layout-contract.mdc`](../../.cursor/rules/layout-contract.mdc) — _RouteEnvelope_) and `@next/codemod` is the standard mechanism for cross-cutting refactors.

### Anti-pattern guardrails

The Working Memory Rail migration (`docs/_draft/working-memory-rail-plan.md`)
established the following permanent rules for **any** shell schema:

- **No decorative status pills.** "Verified", "Live", "Operator" — pills disconnected from action are chrome cosplay. Pressure belongs on nav items as badges with a tone; healthy / steady-state values must disappear, not render "Ready".
- **No ambient context strips.** "Active workspace = Demo Organization" duplicates the utility bar; "Access health = Ready" is tautological. Use **conditional slots** (Phase 3 inbox / views / pinned / recents) that suppress themselves when empty.
- **No marketing description filler.** Schemas must not expose a top-level `description` slot on rail labels (or any shell label literal) whose purpose is to describe the rail to the user. The rail is operator chrome; it explains itself.
- **No hardcoded "online" / status footer.** The footer slot is **optional** and **caller-supplied** (e.g. `<SignOutButton />`). If callers provide nothing, the shell renders nothing — operational truth never lives in fake reassurance.
- **`badge.tone` becomes required** in Phase 2: pressure counts without semantic tone are meaningless integers, not operator signal. The kernel will fail validation for `badge: { count }` without `tone`.

If a future shell surface is tempted to break one of these rules, **update the
kernel schema first** (with a justifying ADR), then propagate to builders via
a codemod. Never let builders fan out fields the kernel does not bless.
